IP (internet protocol)allows data packets to go to their destination and where they are coming from (source). Its often paired with other protocols like TCP to form TCP/IP. an IP packet header is like a packets ID card. The first row contains the Version IHL, Type of service, and total length. version tells us which version of IP is being used (v4 or v6). The IHL (Internet Header Length) tells us the lenght of the header. Tyope of service tells us the packets service tye like if it is focused on speed or cost effectiveness. The total length tells us the overall size of the packet, ncluding its data. Each packet also gets a uniqye identification which is useful for putting together fragemented packets.  IP flags help us know if the pakcet is split into smaller parts or not . Fragment offset: if a packet is split, this field tells us where it starts in a sequence. SOurce address and destination address tel us where the packet os coming from and where it is headed. 

TCP (Transmission control protocol) about establoishing a solid connection.  A TCP header tells us the source port number and destination port number determine the source and destintion ports . The sequence number is a number generated by the senders TCP stack and ensures that packets are arranged in the corrcect order when they arrive. The acknowledgment number echoes back the sequence number confriming the packet has been recieved, if no acknowlegdemnt is recieved within a set time, the sender resend the packet. SYN initiates a new connection. FIN signals the normal closing of a connection ACK acknowledges the receipt of a packet RST indicates a hard close of a connection often used to communicate errors.  URG marks urgent data in the packet PSH directs the data past the buffer to the application.  The window size manages packet bufferng . 

