Address resolution protol (ARP) like a translator for devoces on an ethernet network. It matches up IP addresses which are logical with the MAC addressses which are physical . WHne a new device joins the network ARP assigns it an IP address within the networks rangeand links it to its unique mac address.
Devices use ARP to require the MAC address for that device. When a device needs to communicate with another device, ti already knows the Ip address for the second computer, but does not know the MAC address. The first device will first look at its internal list called the ARP cache to see if the Ip adress fro the second device already has a matching MAC. This can be checked on command promtp (arp -a), if non found none, the device will send a broadcast message on the networking asking every device for which one has the sepecific Ip addres and requesting the MAC in rerturn , the corrsponding comuter will respond bac with thei MAC address and communication can now continue between the two. The MAC address will now be sttored in the ARP cache (arp -a), which makes a network more efficient. 2 different types of ARP entries, dynamic ans static. Dynamic entries are created automatically when a device sends broadcats messages out on the network requesting a MAC, these entries are not permanenet and are flushed out periodicially. A static entry is when somon manually enters an IP to MAC association using the ARP command line utility (arp -s  , then the iP address, followed by the mac address). STatic entries reduc any unecessary ARP broadcast traffic on a network. 

