DNS (Domain Name System), matches web address to IP address. Launch browser and type in a website, the computer may already know th eIp address of the webiste using its stub resolver which checks the cache to see if you have recently been to the website. The IP address might be stored. If not the Stub resolver asks its DNS server (e.g. google(recursive)), if not in its cache, then it go to its roots, which checks the ending of the web address (e.g. .com, which is a TLD, top level domain) and the roots have a list of other DNS servers, and sends the correct server back to google, so google then contacts that DNS server.
DNS is like a translation system that converts a domain name into an IP address. 
